metadata.name: INTERFERENCES #267
metadata.description:
INTERFERENCES is an abstract representation of the incredible collaboration between artists, collectors and developers on fxhash.

Each edition is composed of a multitude of lines representing each individual on the platform. The color of each line defines the role of each individual in this universe. Through their interactions, and the interferences they produce, each line participates in the creation of a common work.

Happy birthday fxhash! And congratulations to all those who work for its success.

Primary sales are donated to the Processing Foundation

[TOUCHSCREEN]
* Double Tap to save the current image

[KEYBOARD]
* Press [S] to save the current image
* Press [1] to save a 1500x2000 pixels PNG
* Press [2] to save a 3000x4000 pixels PNG
* Press [3] to save a 6000x8000 pixels PNG
* Press [0] to save 3 individual SVG for each color set of lines + the background image PNG
* Press [9] to save a grouped SVG of all the lines + the background image PNG

Artist: Estienne
Nov. 2022
NFT License 2.0

Credits to Piter Pasma (@piterpasma) for the Reumann-Witkam line simplification algorithm used in this generator

metadata.name: Soragna #383
metadata.description:
Soragna is an abstract generative series reproducing the effect of paint strokes.
The fundamental element of this system is an object composed of two lines which oscillate perpendicular to the direction of movement. A little like a bird flapping its wings, each element moves on the canvas, leaving behind it the imprint of its passage.

Variability of editions is ensured by:
- 18 color palettes (including 4 rare)
- possibility to combine 2 different palettes
- Constrained directions of the field
- Field symmetries
- Speed, size and size variability of "birds"


To save as a png file, press the following keys:
- [1] for a 2400x4000 pixel image
- [2] for a 4800x8000 pixel image
- [3] for a 7200x12000 pixel image

The image must be recalculated before the chosen dimension can be downloaded. The wait is worth it.



Note regarding the symbolism of the series:

I thought it was interesting to publish this series to celebrate the end of the fxhash beta. The artists on fxhash are like these birds leaving behind them the trace of their passage on the site. Their paths are sometimes parallel, they can cross and even sometimes come together to produce unique collaborations.

Thank you to all the artists and collectors for making the last few months an incredible journey! The best is still to come ...

Artist: Estienne
March 2022
License: NFT 2.0

metadata.name: .discharge #73
metadata.description:
".discharge" is created at a resolution of 1000 x 1000 to express a jewel-like texture and a discharge-like appearance.

As time passes, the overall atmosphere changes as the blurring expression is emphasized while the saturation of the background becomes darker or becomes lighter.

Press 's(S)' to save a PNG.
Press 'o(O)' to save an Original Pixel PNG (1000 x 1000).
Press 'p(P)' pause / resume
Mouse click to full screen

Generative art by @ConatusLab

Built in Javascript with p5.js.

Press 's(S)' to save a png.

metadata.name: When we were Kids #119
metadata.description:
When we were kids.

A work that goes back to our childhood.
When I was a kid I loved spending time with my grandmother and parents, we took a lot of walks with them, looked at different houses, spent time in nature, painted and in general were very much involved in the creative component, it was my parents and grandmother who instilled in me a love for creativity.

Probably one of the few things that have survived to these days is my childhood drawings, a little funny, sloppy, but so real and sincere.

In this work I wanted to take me back to those carefree times and remember with what eagerness and zeal I tried every day to learn something new or to go further than before.

None of this would have happened without my family, for which I am truly grateful.

10% of primary sales will be donated to Cure Parkinson's, I hope all children will have a childhood where they can spend time with their loved ones.

Be patient, some variations take a little longer to render.

Press S for Save Canvas as PNG.

By aleks.ustya, @ALEKUSTN. Made with p5js.

metadata.name: Skies and Lands #53
metadata.description:
Skies and Lands is a collection of generative art featuring a house as the protagonist in an endless array of distinct landscapes. Each piece in the collection showcases a unique representation of the house located in different lands, with varied and dramatic skies providing a captivating contrast. The combination of the static architecture with the constantly changing landscape creates a stunning and never-before-seen visual experience. "Skies and Lands" collection invites the viewer to explore new perspectives and to enjoy the beauty of architecture and nature together. A timeless work of art that will undoubtedly delight art and nature lovers alike.

Don't miss the chance to own a piece of this unique and captivating collection.

metadata.name: Hillhouse #35
metadata.description:
On every important holiday of my childhood, I would return to my hometown, a village in a hilly area. The mist in the morning would have a psychedelic texture, like water ripples under the smudge of the deep blue sky. But at sunrise, the atmosphere becomes lively. All year round, spring, summer, autumn and winter, colourful and dreamlike.

The buildings in my hometown are white walls and black tiles. The fog in the village is very close to the ground, and the terrain is relatively undulating. I can often see rows of angular eaves and white walls penetrating the fog on other hillsides, like houses standing in the clouds. At that time, I always liked to climb up the hillside under the sunset after dinner, looking down at the village surrounded by clouds and mist after the rain. I could always stay at the top of the mountain and watch the clouds change from orange-red to blue. I didn't leave until the sky turned completely black. After I left the village, whenever I described such a scene with my friends, I would call such a building: Hillhouse.

I'm not in China now, and I don't know when I'll be able to see the misty landscape of my hometown again to create Hillhouse, a memorial to the village that inspired my aesthetics during my childhood.

I noticed many of my friends said after seeing my works that my townhouse is like a mountain. My original idea was to appropriately enlarge the proportion of the roof in the picture because I tried to balance the natural landscape and humanistic value in the work. Moreover, I also deliberately strengthened the corners and some obvious small pavilion buildings to make it different from the mountains. But, of course, art depends on personal understanding, so that's fine.


Mint at 188 tez, I will provide a 1/1 customised video NFT, physical printed work, and one WL spot for my following 2 projects on fxhash. You can choose your favourite palette and mountain style in our UI system and the soundtrack first. Then I will create a 20-sec video version NFT for you. The sound is originally created by @Dreminor. 

In terms of printed work, it will be printed on museum quality acid-free paper by giclee print technique. It will never fade 100 yrs. And the printed work will have my signature and seal on it. So yes I will give it to you with no charge, except the delivery fee requested from the delivery company.

I also considered secondary market transactions for collectors who minted at 188. I will offer a NEW customized video NFT and a NEW printed work to collectors who purchase the token minted in 188tez for more than 188tez on the secondary market. The video NFT is free but I will charge 100tez for the new printed work.

Mint at 138 tez, I will provide a printed work and one WL spot for my next project on fxhash.

Mint at 64 tez. I will provide one WL spot for my next project on fxhash.


Btw, the computational expense in this project is high, so if you cannot open live, please try to use a better computer to generate or use Visual Studio Code. If you cannot solve this problem, feel free to contact me, I would like to offer help.

Due to some reasons, the preview will be different from the generative artwork. So pls open live to have a look and it will be much better than preview.

This project is created by Arctic--Cc and Van.

metadata.name: volcans (audio) #7
metadata.description:
-NOTE: Headphones recomended. Some extreme sounds (frequency and amplitude) can be generated.

-From 2 to 12 volcanos will appear sequentially.

-Each volcano is assigned a pair of oscillators (carrier and modulator) in order to create an AM modulation.

-Some volcanos can generate noise.

Features:

    "numVolcans": number of volcanos (2 to 12)
    "color": gray, blue, green or red
    "size_of_cells": terrain resolution (less is more)
    "noise": true or false
    "highest": highest volcano
    "max_diam": biggest diameter
    "max_noise": max noise escale
    "night": true or false.

powered by 5js and p5.sound

metadata.name: The Gap #19
metadata.description:
The Gap is an impressive generative art collection that showcases nature in its purest and most elemental form. At the center of the piece is a break between two walls of ice.
 The break appears to have been created by relentless ice pressure, and its shape and size are a result of the complex interaction between water, ice, and underlying geology.
But what truly captures the viewer's attention are the brilliant colors surrounding the break. The sky is depicted in a warm, brilliant color, while the break is depicted in a cold, brilliant color. These flat, saturated colors create a striking contrast that makes the break stand out in the landscape. Together, these colors create a vibrant and evocative atmosphere that invites viewers to dive into the landscape and explore its details.
In summary, The Gap is a unique work that combines technology and nature to create a stunning and impactful visual experience. With its contrast of warm and cold, brilliant flat colors, this work is a statement about the strength and simplicity of nature, and a call to action to protect our planet.

metadata.name: Nostalgia #40
metadata.description:
When i was a little girl in kindergarten, i was fascinated by colors.
Ever since then i loved the tactile sensation of putting my fingers in the paint and applying it directly to the paper.

The visual aesthetic would be inspired by the bright and playful environment of a kindergarten classroom, evoking feelings of nostalgia and joy for all the collectors.

Press "S" to save as PNG.
